# Antigravity OS: Kaggle Guardian Agent Configuration Blueprint

This document outlines the exact architectural setup and configuration required for the Antigravity system to safely operate on Kaggle competitions, ensuring the agent strictly adheres to [GEMINI.md](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/GEMINI.md) and does not "mess up" ("brljavi").

## 1. Directory Structure (The "Brain")
To ensure the Antigravity Agent has all the rules, the workspace must be structured so the agent can RAG (Retrieve and Generate) or inject them directly into the system prompt.

```text
/home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/
├── .gemini/                 # Default memory storage for the agent
├── GEMINI.md                # The Single Source of Truth (The Constitution)
├── .agents/                 
│   └── workflows/           # Pre-approved routines (e.g., mistral_trigger.md)
├── scripts/
│   └── kaggle_process_guard_llm.py # The script that forces JSON constraints
└── trinity_config.json      # Dynamic overrides (e.g., CPU limits, OOF thresholds)
```

## 2. Antigravity Agent System Prompt Injection
The agent needs to know its boundaries. The Antigravity system config (`.gemini/system_prompt.txt` or similar) must be updated to include the following strict directive:

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **System Prompt Directive for the Agent:**
> "You are the Antigravity AI Agent operating under the Trinity Protocol. 
> 1. Before executing any code, you MUST consult [GEMINI.md](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/GEMINI.md).
> 2. You MUST adhere to dynamic thresholds defined in [trinity_config.json](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/trinity_config.json).
> 3. If you plan a risky Kaggle action (e.g., pseudo-labeling on synthetic data), you MUST first run [scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py) and strictly follow its VETO/WARNING output.
> 4. You are forbidden from ignoring the Guard's VETO. If a VETO is triggered, immediately halt training, document the failure in [GUARD_LOG.md](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/GUARD_LOG.md), and switch to the `actionable_fallback` response."

## 3. How the Kaggle Guardian Secures the Agent
The [kaggle_process_guard_llm.py](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py) script we created acts as a **hard checkpoint** (Rule 48). 
- Every time the agent creates a training plan, it formats it as a string and passes it to the [KaggleProcessGuardLLM](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py#15-100).
- The LLM has the *entire* [GEMINI.md](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/GEMINI.md) in its context window.
- If the agent hallucinates a bad idea (e.g., "I will use Fox formula for MaxHR instead of Tanaka"), the Guardian catches it, returns `{"severity_level": "VETO"}`, and the Python code raises an exception.
- This exception forces the Antigravity Agent to stop what it's doing and re-evaluate, preventing it from wasting Kaggle GPU hours.

## 4. Packing the Core Knowledge for New Environments
If you are moving to a new machine or a clean Kaggle instance, the minimal viable core is:
1. [GEMINI.md](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/GEMINI.md)
2. [trinity_config.json](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/trinity_config.json)
3. [scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py](file:///home/kizabgd/Desktop/Istrazivanje/scripts/kaggle_process_guard_llm.py)
4. `.agents/workflows/`

The Antigravity system reads `.agents/workflows/` automatically to know which specific commands are pre-approved (like `!Mistral`).

## Implementation Tasks required for this configuration:
- [ ] Ensure Antigravity core reads `GEMINI.md` on startup.
- [ ] Inject the System Prompt Directive (Step 2) into the agent's baseline instructions.
- [ ] Map the `!Mistral` or `/mistral` command to invoke the Guardian script automatically before expensive `model.fit()` calls.
